<SUMMARY MODIFIED="2012-11-22 01:22:05 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Jessica Sharp">
<TITLE MODIFIED="2012-11-22 01:22:05 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Jessica Sharp">[Summary title]</TITLE>
<SUMMARY_BODY MODIFIED="2012-11-22 01:21:39 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Jessica Sharp">
<P>
<MARKER>The PLS must summarise the review in straightforward language which can be understood by the lay reader. Use simple sentences and short paragraphs. The PLS must include: </MARKER>
</P>
<P>
<MARKER>Description of the healthcare problem (symptoms, etc) and the intervention; </MARKER>
</P>
<P>
<MARKER>A statement about why the review is important;</MARKER>
</P>
<P>
<MARKER>Number of studies and 'people' (not participants) included;</MARKER>
</P>
<P>
<MARKER>Main findings of the review (written explanation, no numerical results);</MARKER>
</P>
<P>
<MARKER>A brief summary of any limitations of the review.</MARKER>
</P>
</SUMMARY_BODY>
</SUMMARY>
<ABSTRACT MODIFIED="2012-11-22 01:12:06 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion">
<ABS_BACKGROUND MODIFIED="2012-11-22 01:12:06 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Jessica Sharp">
<P>
<MARKER>Remember the abstract will be freely available online and must serve as a stand-alone document. For some helpful tips on how to write it, see</MARKER> http://ccdan.cochrane.org/abstract-guidance-authors</P>
</ABS_BACKGROUND>
<ABS_OBJECTIVES MODIFIED="2011-03-29 02:36:33 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion"/>
<ABS_SEARCH_STRATEGY MODIFIED="2011-03-29 02:36:36 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion"/>
<ABS_SELECTION_CRITERIA MODIFIED="2011-03-29 02:36:40 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion"/>
<ABS_DATA_COLLECTION MODIFIED="2011-03-29 02:36:42 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion"/>
<ABS_RESULTS/>
<ABS_CONCLUSIONS/>
</ABSTRACT>
<BODY MODIFIED="2014-11-03 15:02:02 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Christopher Gale">
<BACKGROUND MODIFIED="2012-10-15 16:06:37 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion">
<CONDITION MODIFIED="2012-10-15 16:06:37 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Generalised anxiety disorder (GAD) is a common psychiatric disorder. The key symptom is disproportionate worry about many if not most activities and concerns of daily living (<LINK REF="REF-Tyrer-2006" TYPE="REFERENCE">Tyrer 2006</LINK>). This is associated with somatic symptoms of anxiety, such as trembling, shaking, poor co-ordination, muscle ache, sweating, nausea, diarrhoea and an exaggerated startle response (<LINK REF="REF-APA-2000" TYPE="REFERENCE">APA 2000</LINK>). Other symptoms include being easily fatigued and difficulty concentrating. Patients can be irritable and have disturbed sleep (<LINK REF="REF-APA-2000" TYPE="REFERENCE">APA 2000</LINK>). GAD has been associated with considerable comorbidity (<LINK REF="REF-Wittchen-2002" TYPE="REFERENCE">Wittchen 2002</LINK>), decreased quality of life and significant disability (<LINK REF="REF-Revicki-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Revicki 2011</LINK>).</P>
<P>The point prevalence of GAD has been estimated at 1.6%, the 12-month prevalence at 3.1% and the lifetime prevalence at 5.1% in the US National Co-morbidity Survey (<LINK REF="REF-Wittchen-2002" TYPE="REFERENCE">Wittchen 2002</LINK>). The lifetime prevalence in US adolescents was 3.0% (standard error (SE) 0.6%) for women and 1.5% (SE 0.3%) for men; among the total adolescent population 0.9% (SE 0.2%) were considered to be severely impaired due to GAD (<LINK REF="REF-Merikangas-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Merikangas 2010</LINK>). GAD is more common in women, in those who are from lower socioeconomic groups, or who are widowed, separated or divorced (<LINK REF="REF-Grant-2005" TYPE="REFERENCE">Grant 2005</LINK>). The female to male ratio is 3:1 (<LINK REF="REF-Lim-2005" TYPE="REFERENCE">Lim 2005</LINK>); men are more likely to have co-occurring substance abuse than women (odds ratio 3.40, 95% confidence interval 2.59 to 4.47) (<LINK REF="REF-Alegria-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Alegria 2010</LINK>). However, these rates need to be considered with caution. Two-step designs (a screening test then clinical interview) reveal different results. For example, in a survey of primary care patients, 22% of 7900 patients met the criteria using a structured screening interview <LINK REF="REF-Romera-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Romera 2010</LINK>. However, a clinician performing the structured clinical interview for DSM_IV&lt; (SCID) estimated the point prevalence in primary care at 3.8% (<LINK REF="REF-Serrano_x002d_Blanco-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Serrano-Blanco 2010</LINK>). A survey of rural Californian patients using a two-stage design found that 28% of their patients had GAD diagnosed using the Mini-International Neuropsychiatric Interview (<LINK REF="REF-Marks-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Marks 2010</LINK>).</P>
<P>A series of treatments have been used for GAD. These include non-pharmacological treatments such as applied relaxation and cognitive therapy (<LINK REF="REF-Covin-2008" TYPE="REFERENCE">Covin 2008</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-Hofmann-2008" TYPE="REFERENCE">Hofmann 2008</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-Hunot-2007" TYPE="REFERENCE">Hunot 2007</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-Mitte-2005" TYPE="REFERENCE">Mitte 2005</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-Otte-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Otte 2011</LINK>) and pharmacological treatments including antidepressants (<LINK REF="REF-Kapczinski-2003" TYPE="REFERENCE">Kapczinski 2003</LINK>), azapirones (<LINK REF="REF-Chessick-2006" TYPE="REFERENCE">Chessick 2006</LINK>), benzodiazepines, hydroxyzine (<LINK REF="REF-Guaiana-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Guaiana 2010</LINK>), the herb kava (<LINK REF="REF-Sarris-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Sarris 2011</LINK>), pregabalin (<LINK REF="REF-Samuel-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Samuel 2011</LINK>) and antipsychotics (<LINK REF="REF-Depping-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Depping 2010</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-LaLonde-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">LaLonde 2011</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-Maher-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Maher 2011</LINK>). The herb valerian has been studied in clinical trials, but the results are equivocal (<LINK REF="REF-Miyasaka-2006" TYPE="REFERENCE">Miyasaka 2006</LINK>). In general, cognitive therapy is seen as the treatment of choice (<LINK REF="REF-Gale-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Gale 2011</LINK>), followed by antidepressants, particularly fluoxetine and sertraline (<LINK REF="REF-Baldwin-2011a" TYPE="REFERENCE">Baldwin 2011a</LINK>). In older people, psychological and pharmacological interventions have similar effect sizes (<LINK REF="REF-Goncalves-2012" TYPE="REFERENCE">Goncalves 2012</LINK>).</P>
</CONDITION>
<INTERVENTION MODIFIED="2012-10-15 16:01:10 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Chris Champion">
<P>Benzodiazepines are highly effective in the short-term management of GAD (<LINK REF="REF-Mitte-2005" TYPE="REFERENCE">Mitte 2005</LINK>). A Cochrane systematic review suggests that benzodiazepines are more effective than azapirones in treating GAD (<LINK REF="REF-Chessick-2006" TYPE="REFERENCE">Chessick 2006</LINK>). Benzodiazepines were developed as a treatment for anxiety neurosis, which was the term previously used for anxiety disorders in general, including what became generalised anxiety disorder in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) III (<LINK REF="REF-Wolk-1996" TYPE="REFERENCE">Wolk 1996</LINK>). The original clinical trials for this class of medication date from the early 1960s (<LINK REF="REF-Grosser-1965" TYPE="REFERENCE">Grosser 1965</LINK>; <LINK REF="REF-Nesselhof-1965" TYPE="REFERENCE">Nesselhof 1965</LINK>), before the separation of GAD from other anxiety disorders. Benzodiazepines have been widely used in anxiety disorders of all types, including generalised anxiety disorder. There is no evidence from clinical trials to support longer-term usage (greater than four to six weeks).</P>
<P>Benzodiazepines have several problems limiting widespread applicability. There is a significant risk of dependency and withdrawal syndrome (<LINK REF="REF-Rickels-1990" TYPE="REFERENCE">Rickels 1990</LINK>). This may represent a problem in clinical practice, given the chronic nature of GAD. Impaired cognitive function, rebound anxiety and withdrawal syndromes can occur and may influence therapy, especially in the long term (<LINK REF="REF-Uzun-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Uzun 2010</LINK>). Among older people, benzodiazepines may be associated with falls and increased risk of hip fractures <LINK REF="REF-Zint-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Zint 2010</LINK>.</P>
<P>Despite the lack of an evidence base for long-term use and these difficulties, benzodiazepines are used for longer than recommended and for reasons not advised in standard guidelines (<LINK REF="REF-Manthey-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Manthey 2011</LINK>).</P>
</INTERVENTION>
<THEORY MODIFIED="2012-10-15 16:03:04 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Benzodiazepines interact with a specific binding site on the GABA-A receptor. This binding site is at the interface of the alpha and gamma subunits, and only for alpha subunits that contain a histidine residue (i.e. alpha-1, alpha-2, alpha-3 and alpha-5 containing GABA-A receptors) (<LINK REF="REF-Rabow-1995" TYPE="REFERENCE">Rabow 1995</LINK>). Benzodiazepines are allosteric modulators: by themselves, they cannot open the GABA-A receptor chloride ion channel, however they enhance the affinity of the receptor for GABA <LINK REF="REF-Sancar-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Sancar 2011</LINK>. Functionally, this increases the frequency of the opening of the chloride ion channel in response to GABA binding. This enhanced inhibition is manifested clinically as reduced anxiety and increased sedation.</P>
</THEORY>
<IMPORTANCE MODIFIED="2012-10-15 16:04:26 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Benzodiazepines continue to be used in the treatment of GAD (<LINK REF="REF-Baldwin-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Baldwin 2011</LINK>). Current reviews of benzodiazepines evaluate and compare the side effect profile of benzodiazepines with other medications, however their focus is the effectiveness of other types of treatments for GAD such as hydroxyzine (<LINK REF="REF-Guaiana-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Guaiana 2010</LINK>), antidepressants, (<LINK REF="REF-Kapczinski-2003" TYPE="REFERENCE">Kapczinski 2003</LINK>), atypical antipsychotics (<LINK REF="REF-Depping-2010" TYPE="REFERENCE">Depping 2010</LINK>) and azapirones (<LINK REF="REF-Chessick-2006" TYPE="REFERENCE">Chessick 2006</LINK>). There is a risk that these reviews will miss various benzodiazepine trials. Other systematic reviews (such as <LINK REF="REF-Gale-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Gale 2011</LINK>) do not recalculate the previously published meta-analysis with subsequent papers but instead describe them. There is thus a need to systematically review benzodiazepines directly. The recent finding that benzodiazepines may have a greater effect size than antidepressants in older people (<LINK REF="REF-Goncalves-2012" TYPE="REFERENCE">Goncalves 2012</LINK>) also warrants study.</P>
</IMPORTANCE>
</BACKGROUND>
<OBJECTIVES MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:43:10 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>The objectives of this review are to assess the effects of any benzodiazepine for the treatment of generalised anxiety disorder (GAD) in participants from any setting. [These need to be changed]</P>
<OL>
<LI>To investigate the efficacy and acceptability of benzodiazepines in the treatment of generalised anxiety disorder compared with pregabalin.</LI>
</OL>
</OBJECTIVES>
<METHODS MODIFIED="2014-06-09 15:26:21 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<SELECTION_CRITERIA MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:54:57 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<CRIT_STUDIES MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:43:26 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]" NOTES="&lt;p&gt;There is an ongoing problem with the GAD literature. Most people with GAD have co occuring anxiety and depressive disorders. However, most of the literature comes from trials designed to meet FDA/ EU criteria, and exclude people with comorbidity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are some trials using quasi randomised designs -- generally not cluster or crossover -- that are effectiveness trials and include co morbidities. I think we should include these trials as a secondary analysis, where they exist. I'd normally write this as &amp;quot;we will include quasi randomised, including cluster and cross over trials of patients with co morbid anxiety disorders if participants have a primary diagnosis of GAD&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;" NOTES_MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:43:26 +1200" NOTES_MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>All randomised controlled trials (RCTs), including any cluster-randomised studies. We excluded cross-over randomised controlled trials.</P>
</CRIT_STUDIES>
<CRIT_PARTICIPANTS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:53:38 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Participants were adults (as defined by the study authors) of both sexes, with a primary diagnosis of GAD. Studies adopting any criteria to define participants suffering from GAD were included. More recent studies are likely to have used DSM-IV-TR (<LINK REF="REF-APA-2000" TYPE="REFERENCE">APA 2000</LINK>), DSM-IV (<LINK REF="REF-APA-1994" TYPE="REFERENCE">APA 1994</LINK>) or International Classification of Diseases (ICD)-10 (<LINK REF="REF-WHO-1992" TYPE="REFERENCE">WHO 1992</LINK>) criteria. Older studies may have used ICD-9 (<LINK REF="REF-WHO-1978" TYPE="REFERENCE">WHO 1978</LINK>), DSM-III (<LINK REF="REF-APA-1980" TYPE="REFERENCE">APA 1980</LINK>)/DSM-III-R (<LINK REF="REF-APA-1987" TYPE="REFERENCE">APA 1987</LINK>) or other diagnostic systems. A concurrent diagnosis of a medical disorder is an exclusion criterion, but studies including participants with co-occurring psychiatric disorders were included if the primary diagnosis for inclusion was GAD. We accepted studies from any setting.</P>
</CRIT_PARTICIPANTS>
<CRIT_INTERVENTIONS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:53:58 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>The benzodiazepine group of medications includes: alprazolam, bretazenil, bromazepam, chlordiazepoxide, cinolazepam, clonazepam, cloxazolam, clorazepate, diazepam, estazolam, fludiazepam, flunitrazepam, flurazepam, flutoprazepam, halazepam, ketazolam, loprazolam, lorazepam, medazepam, nimatazepam, nitrazepam, nordazepam, oxazepam, phenazepam, pinazepam, prazepam, premazepam, quazepam, temazepam, tetrazepam and triazolam. The atypical benzodiazepine ligands (sometimes referred to as 'non-benzodiazepines') include clobazam, eszopiclone, zaleplon, zolpidem and zopiclone.</P>
<P>We intended to split the analysis between the typical and atypical benzodiazepines and then pool them but this was not possible.</P>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Comparator intervention</HEADING>
<P>Pregabalin. There are no restrictions on dosage, frequency or intensity of treatment. We intended to separately analyse trials of 12 weeks duration, but we did not find any (see below).</P>
</SUBSECTION>
</CRIT_INTERVENTIONS>
<CRIT_OUTCOMES MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:54:57 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<CRIT_OUTCOMES_PRIMARY MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:54:57 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Our primary outcomes are response rate and acceptability.</P>
<P>We defined response rate as the number of participants showing a response measured as a reduction of at least 50% on the Hamilton Anxiety Scale (HAM-A) (<LINK REF="REF-Hamilton-1959" TYPE="REFERENCE">Hamilton 1959</LINK>). In addition, we will collect Clinical Global Impression (CGI) - severity scale scores (<LINK REF="REF-Guy-1976" TYPE="REFERENCE">Guy 1976</LINK>). We considered as "response" a CGI-S (severity) criteria score of one, two or three and CGI-I (improvement) criteria score of one or two.</P>
<P>We evaluated acceptability using the following outcome measures (where available).</P>
<UL>
<LI>Number of patients who dropped out during the trial as a proportion of the total number of randomised patients (total drop-out rate).</LI>
<LI>Number of patients who dropped out during the trial, as a proportion of the total number of randomised patients, due to inefficacy, as described by the authors.</LI>
<LI>Number of patients who dropped out during the trial, as a proportion of the total number of randomised patients, due to side effects.</LI>
</UL>
<P>It is anticipated that most of the data will be from trials of less than 12 weeks' duration. We analysed data for any trials lasting over 12 weeks separately.</P>
</CRIT_OUTCOMES_PRIMARY>
<CRIT_OUTCOMES_SECONDARY MODIFIED="2014-05-12 14:19:12 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>We assessed the following secondary outcomes.</P>
<UL>
<LI>Remission as measured as by (i) the number of participants showing 17 or less on the 14-item HAM-A (<LINK REF="REF-Hamilton-1959" TYPE="REFERENCE">Hamilton 1959</LINK>), (ii) any other similar cut-off value on an anxiety scale, depending on the study authors' definition, (iii) 'not ill or borderline mentally ill' (a score one or two) on CGI - severity (<LINK REF="REF-Guy-1976" TYPE="REFERENCE">Guy 1976</LINK>), or (iv) according to authors' definition of remitters at follow-up.</LI>
<LI>Change in symptom levels. Group mean scores at the end of the trial on (i) Hamilton Anxiety Scale, (ii) any other anxiety scale, or (iii) CGI - severity scale (using standardised mean difference).</LI>
<LI>General and specific adverse effects (separate from those collected for tolerability).</LI>
<LI>Significant change in quality of life/satisfaction - as defined by each of the studies.</LI>
<LI>Satisfaction with care for either recipients of care or carers.</LI>
<LI>Average score/change in quality of life/satisfaction.</LI>
<LI>Death.</LI>
</UL>
<P>We will evaluate tolerability using the following outcome measures.</P>
<UL>
<LI>Total number of patients experiencing the following specific side effects:</LI>
</UL>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>Sleepiness/drowsiness</LI>
<LI>Falls</LI>
<LI>Hypotension</LI>
<LI>Agitation/anxiety</LI>
<LI>Suicide wishes/gestures/attempts</LI>
<LI>Completed suicide</LI>
<LI>Subjective memory impairment</LI>
</UL>
</UL>
<UL>
<LI>Total number of patients experiencing withdrawal symptoms</LI>
<LI>Any self reported measures of intolerance or side effects</LI>
</UL>
</CRIT_OUTCOMES_SECONDARY>
</CRIT_OUTCOMES>
</SELECTION_CRITERIA>
<SEARCH_METHODS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:55:25 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="3">Cochrane Depression, Anxiety and Neurosis (CCDAN) Group Specialised Register (CCDANCTR)</HEADING>
<P>The Cochrane Depression, Anxiety and Neurosis Group (CCDAN) maintain two clinical trials registers at their editorial base in Bristol, UK, a references register and a studies-based register. The CCDANCTR-References register contains over 29,500 reports of randomised controlled trials in depression, anxiety and neurosis. Approximately 65% of these references have been tagged to individual, coded trials. The coded trials are held in the CCDANCTR-Studies register and records are linked between the two registers through the use of unique Study ID tags. Coding of trials is based on the EU-Psi coding manual. Please contact the CCDAN Trials Search Co-ordinator for further details. Reports of trials for inclusion in the Group's registers are collated from routine (weekly), generic searches of MEDLINE (1950 -), EMBASE (1974 -) and PsycINFO (1967 -), quarterly searches of the Cochrane Central Register of Controlled Trials (CENTRAL) and review-specific searches of additional databases. Reports of trials are also sourced from international trials registers c/o the World Health Organization&#8217;s trials portal (<A HREF="http://apps.who.int/trialsearch/">ICTRP</A>), drug companies, the handsearching of key journals, conference proceedings and other (non-Cochrane) systematic reviews and meta-analyses. Details of <A HREF="http://ccdan.cochrane.org/search-strategies-identification-studies">CCDAN's generic search strategies</A> can be found on the Group's website.</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<ELECTRONIC_SEARCHES MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:55:25 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>We searched the CCDANCTR (Studies and References) using the following search terms:</P>
<P>("Generalized Anxiety" or "Generalised Anxiety" or GAD) and (Benzodiazepin* or BZD or Abecarnil or Adinazolam or Alprazolam or Arfendazam or Bentazepam or Bretazenil or Bromazepam or Brotizolam or Camazepam or Chlordiazepoxide or Chlordesmethyldiazepam or Cinolazepam or Clobazam or Clonazepam or Clorazepate or Clotiazepam or Cloxazolam or Delorazepam or Demoxepam or<B>
<I> </I>
</B>Desmethyldiazepam or Desoxydemoxepam or Devazepide or Diazepam or Doxefazepam or Estazolam or &#8220;ethyl loflazepate&#8221; or &#8220;CM 6912&#8221; or CM-6912 or Etizolam or Fludiazepam or Flunitrazepam or Flurazepam or dealkylflurazepam or Flutoprazepam or Fosazepam or Gidazepam or Girisopam or Halazepam or Haloxazolam or Ketazolam or Loflazepate or Loprazolam or Lorazepam or Lormetazepam or Meclonazepam or Medazepam or Metaclazepam or Mexazolam or Midazolam or Nerisopam or Nimetazepam or Nitrazepam or Norchlordiazepoxide or Norclobazam or Nordazepam or Norfludiazepam or Norflunitrazepam or Oxazepam or &#8220;WY 3498&#8221; or WY-3498 or Oxazolam or Phenazepam or Pinazepam or Prazepam or Premazepam or Propazepam or Quazepam or Ripazepam or Serazepine or Sograzepide or Talampanel or Tarazepide or Temazepam or Tetrazepam or Tofisopam or Triazolam or (Zolazepam or Zaleplon or Zolpidem or Zopiclone or Eszopiclone or Z-Drugs or &#8220;Z Drugs&#8221;))</P>
<P>We will carry out additional searches on the WHO Trials Portal (<A HREF="http://apps.who.int/trialsearch/">ICTRP</A>) and <A HREF="http://www.clinicaltrials.gov">ClinicalTrials.gov</A> to identify any unpublished or ongoing studies.</P>
</ELECTRONIC_SEARCHES>
<OTHER_SEARCHES MODIFIED="2012-10-10 23:32:38 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Bibliographies</HEADING>
<P>We will examine references and bibliographies from the text of reports of relevant trials for further RCTs not yet identified.</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Personal communication</HEADING>
<P>We will consult leading researchers and authors of included studies to find out if they know of any published, unpublished or ongoing RCTs in the area that are not identified by other means. We will contact the manufacturers of agents of interest to request additional data from unpublished studies.</P>
</SUBSECTION>
</OTHER_SEARCHES>
</SEARCH_METHODS>
<DATA_COLLECTION MODIFIED="2014-06-09 15:26:21 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<STUDY_SELECTION MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:57:48 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Two members of the research team scanned abstracts of the studies generated by the searches. Those studies that meet the following rough inclusion criteria will constitute the preliminary list and we will retrieve their full texts. The rough inclusion criteria are:</P>
<OL>
<LI>randomised trial;</LI>
<LI>comparing benzodiazepines against placebo or any other anxiolytic;</LI>
<LI>in people with GAD, regardless of the diagnostic criteria used.</LI>
</OL>
<P>We then assessed all the full-text articles in this preliminary list to see if they meet the strict inclusion criteria. When the raters disagreed, the final rating was made by consensus with the involvement of another member of the review group. We reported non-congruence in the selection of trials as percentage disagreement. We grouped duplicate publications of the same trial as multiple references to one study.</P>
</STUDY_SELECTION>
<DATA_EXTRACTION MODIFIED="2014-06-03 09:58:00 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Two review authors independently extracted data using a specially designed form. We discussed any disagreement with a third review author (PH), document the decisions and, where necessary, contact the authors of the studies to help resolve the issue.</P>
<P>The main comparisons are benzodiazepines versus the following comparators (response rate, acceptability, secondary outcomes).</P>
<OL>
<LI>Pregabalin</LI>
</OL>
</DATA_EXTRACTION>
<QUALITY_ASSESSMENT MODIFIED="2014-06-09 15:26:21 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Two review authors independently assessed the risk of bias within each included study based on the following six domains as per the <I>Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions</I> (<LINK REF="REF-Higgins-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Higgins 2011</LINK>):</P>
<OL>
<LI>The method used to generate the allocation sequence should be described in detail so that we can assess whether it should have produced comparable groups.</LI>
<LI>The method used to conceal the allocation sequence should be described in sufficient detail so that we can assess whether intervention schedules could have been predicted in advance of, or during, recruitment.</LI>
<LI>We assessed whether the method by which any measures used to blind (mask) participants, personnel and outcome assessors adequately limits the chance that any person from any group is able to ascertain which intervention a given participant might have received; this should be done separately for different types of outcome.</LI>
<LI>If studies do not report intention-to-treat analyses, we made attempts to obtain missing data by contacting the study authors. We extracted and reported data on attrition and exclusions as well as the numbers involved (compared with total randomised), reasons for attrition/exclusion where reported or obtained from investigators, and any re-inclusions in re-analyses we perform. We will report whether, in our judgement, incomplete data were dealt with adequately (see also <LINK TAG="MISSING_DATA" TYPE="SECTION">Dealing with missing data</LINK>).</LI>
<LI>We made attempts to assess the possibility of selective outcome reporting by investigators. We will rate these items as 'high', 'low' or 'unclear' using the methods described in chapter eight of the <I>Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions</I>.</LI>
<LI>We also considered and reported whether we consider there were any other factors that could put a study at a high risk of bias. We will perform a sensitivity analysis excluding any studies with high risk of bias.</LI>
</OL>
</QUALITY_ASSESSMENT>
<EFFECT_MEASURES MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:00:03 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>We analysed dichotomous outcomes by calculating risk ratios for each trial with the uncertainty in each result expressed using confidence intervals. We described continuous outcomes using mean differences or, if more than one scale is considered to measure the same thing, using standardised mean differences.</P>
<P>Data on continuous outcomes are frequently skewed, the mean not being the centre of the distribution. The statistics for meta-analysis are thought to be able to cope with some skew, but were formulated for normally distributed data. We took appropriate care to assure that potentially skewed data do not have undue influence.</P>
<P>Where both change and endpoint data are available for the same outcome category we will only present endpoint data. We contacted authors of studies reporting only change data for endpoint figures. We reported non-normally distributed data that may adversely affect the results in a table.</P>
</EFFECT_MEASURES>
<UNIT_OF_ANALYSIS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:01:29 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Cluster-randomised trials</HEADING>
<P>For included studies that employ a 'cluster-randomisation' study design (such as randomisation by clinician or practice), we first assessed whether clustering has been accounted for by the authors, in order to reduce the possibility of a unit of analysis error (<LINK REF="REF-Divine-1992" TYPE="REFERENCE">Divine 1992</LINK>). Where clustering is not accounted for in primary studies, we contacted first authors of studies to obtain the intra class correlation co-efficient (ICC) of their clustered data and to adjust for this by using accepted methods (<LINK REF="REF-Higgins-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Higgins 2011</LINK>). Where clustering is adequately accounted for, we included the data as if from a parallel-group randomised study. Where no ICC can be obtained for cluster-randomised studies we incorporated these into the analysis using an inflated variance as suggested in the <I>Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions</I> (<LINK REF="REF-Higgins-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">Higgins 2011</LINK>).</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Cross-over trials</HEADING>
<P>We will excluded cross-over trials as it is quite likely that there will be carry-over effects from the first period of treatment after crossing to the second period of treatment.</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Studies with multiple treatment groups</HEADING>
<P>If a study has multiple arms and benzodiazepines are being used as an active control, then we included the arms of the study as pair-wise comparisons that would meet the criteria for inclusion. Alternatively, if two arms of the trial contain the same or similar medications and the control is placebo, then we combined the arms when the consensus of authors is that this is clinically sensible and appropriate.<BR/>
</P>
</SUBSECTION>
</UNIT_OF_ANALYSIS>
<MISSING_DATA MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:02:40 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>When missing data was found the first approach was to contact the authors. We calculated missing standard deviations from other data if possible. If these methods are not sufficient then we considered imputation of missing data.</P>
<P>If within studies the authors have attempted to correct for missing data, by using multiple imputation or last observation carried forward, then we used these in preference to the completers data, with appropriate care to determine if this makes a substantial difference to results.</P>
</MISSING_DATA>
<HETEROGENEITY_ASSESSMENT MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:03:20 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>We examined heterogeneity between comparable trials using visual inspection of the forest plot and consideration of the I<SUP>2</SUP> statistic. We explored high levels of heterogeneity (where more than 50% of the variability in outcome between trials could not be explained by sampling variation) through the sensitivity analyses specified below. In addition to the I<SUP>
<I>2</I> </SUP>value (<A HREF="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/o/cochrane/clsysrev/articles/CD008339/bibliography.html#CD008339-bbs2-0012">Higgins 2003</A>), we presented the Chi<SUP>2</SUP> test for heterogeneity and its P value and consider the direction and magnitude of the treatment effects.</P>
</HETEROGENEITY_ASSESSMENT>
<BIAS_ASSESSMENT MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:03:31 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>We produced a funnel plot (trial effect versus trial size) if more than 10 trials contribute to a meta-analysis, in an attempt to investigate the likelihood of small sample biases. We will investigate funnel plot asymmetries (suggesting potential publication bias) (<A HREF="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/o/cochrane/clsysrev/articles/CD008339/bibliography.html#CD008339-bbs2-0009">Egger 1997</A>).</P>
</BIAS_ASSESSMENT>
<DATA_SYNTHESIS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:04:07 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>We performed statistical analysis in accordance with the guidelines for statistical analysis in the <I>Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions</I> (<A HREF="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/o/cochrane/clsysrev/articles/CD008339/bibliography.html#CD008339-bbs2-0013">Higgins 2008</A>). We will enter data into Review Manager 5 (<LINK REF="REF-RevMan-2011" TYPE="REFERENCE">RevMan 2011</LINK>).</P>
<P>We combined dichotomous data (e.g. response/not response) using a random-effects model. We also combined continuous data using a random-effects model. We may conduct a fixed-effect analysis as part of a sensitivity analysis.</P>
</DATA_SYNTHESIS>
<SUBGROUP_ANALYSIS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:04:33 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Subgroup analyses was performed and interpreted with caution, because multiple analyses will lead to false positive conclusions (<A HREF="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/o/cochrane/clsysrev/articles/CD006815/bibliography.html#CD006815-bbs2-0021">Oxman 1992</A>). We intended to perform the following subgroup analyses, where possible, for the following a priori reasons:</P>
<OL>
<LI>Diagnosis type: pre DSM III, DSM III and DSM III-TR, DSM IV and following. This is needed as there have been considerable changes in the criteria for GAD between revisions of the DSM. We will analyse studies separately and only combine them if there is no heterogeneity.</LI>
<LI>Treatment settings (psychiatric inpatients, psychiatric outpatients, primary care).</LI>
<LI>Elderly participants (65 years of age or more) versus other adult participants.</LI>
<LI>Trials allowing psychiatric comorbidity versus those excluding such participants.</LI>
<LI>Trials with and without non-standardised response criteria.</LI>
<LI>Excluding trials when benzodiazepines are an add-on treatment compared to trials where benzodiazepines are the only treatment.</LI>
<LI>Trials lasting over 12 weeks: there is a risk that quite short trials will overestimate the efficacy of benzodiazepines as this group of medications work rapidly, while alternative medications such as antidepressants can take some weeks to months to work. The longer trials may thus be less biased.</LI>
</OL>
</SUBGROUP_ANALYSIS>
<SENSITIVITY_ANALYSIS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:05:31 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>The following sensitivity analyses were planned a priori.</P>
<OL>
<LI>Excluding trials with unclear or inadequate concealment of random allocation, unclear or inadequate blinding, or both.</LI>
<LI>Excluding trials whose drop-out rate is greater than 20%.</LI>
<LI>Excluding trials for which the response rates had to be calculated based on the imputation method (<LINK REF="REF-Furukawa-2005" TYPE="REFERENCE">Furukawa 2005</LINK>) and those for which the standard deviation (SD) or ICC had to be borrowed from other trials (<LINK REF="REF-Furukawa-2006" TYPE="REFERENCE">Furukawa 2006</LINK>).</LI>
<LI>Application of fixed-effect models may also be considered to see if the weighting of small studies may be affecting the pooled result.</LI>
</OL>
<P>If subgroups within any of the subgroup or sensitivity analyses were significantly different from one another, we planned to run meta-regression for exploratory analyses of additive or multiplicative influences of the variables in question.<BR/>
</P>
</SENSITIVITY_ANALYSIS>
</DATA_COLLECTION>
</METHODS>
<RESULTS MODIFIED="2014-11-03 15:02:02 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Christopher Gale">
<STUDY_DESCRIPTION MODIFIED="2014-11-03 15:00:39 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Christopher Gale">
<P>
<MARKER>With this section (as with all other sections), remember to right-click the headings to access the relevant advice in the handbook.</MARKER>
</P>
<SEARCH_RESULTS MODIFIED="2014-06-03 10:07:04 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>226 papers initially located were found in a search of the CCDAN trials data base. Of these 6 were comparing pregabalin with benzodiazapines for the specific treatment of generalised anxiety disorder. 4 were found via clinical database searching, 2 were found via handsearching references. A search of clinical trial databases revealed no additional papers. See <LINK TAG="CHARACTERISTICS_OF_INCLUDED_STUDIES" TYPE="SECTION">Characteristics of included studies</LINK>
<BR/>
<BR/>1 of these trials was excluded as it was a pooled meta-analysis from several different sites using drug company data. Two were excluded as they were duplicate references. The remaining three randomised control trials were included for final analysis. See <LINK REF="FIG-03" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 3</LINK>
</P>
</SEARCH_RESULTS>
<INCLUDED_STUDIES_DESCR MODIFIED="2014-11-03 15:00:39 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Christopher Gale">
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">Design</HEADING>
<P>All trials were randomised double-blind blind comparisons of a benzodiazepine with pregabalin.</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">Sample sizes</HEADING>
<P>The sample sizes in all papers ranged between 271 and 454 participants entered into an intention to treat analysis. .</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">Setting</HEADING>
<P>All studies involved outpatients, with some recruitment from local newspapers.</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">Participants</HEADING>
<P>All papers used DSM-IV criteria for GAD. One paper allowed co morbidity(<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>); two papers did not (<LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>).</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">Interventions.</HEADING>
<P>All trials used a fixed dose design with multiple pregabalin arms with doses varying between 150 mg./d and 600 mg./d. All studies used fixed, not flexible doses. The benzodiazepine used as a comparison varied between papers being lorazepam in two papers (<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>) and alprazolam in the final paper (<LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>)</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">Outcomes</HEADING>
<P>All papers reported as their primary outcome the change in Hamilton Anxiety Scale score (HAM-A) at the end of four weeks, or day 28. All papers also reported clinical global improvement, in a dichotomous fashion, and all used a method of reporting side effects. Two papers reported the physicians withdrawal checklist (<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>) and one paper reported the Endicott Work Productivity Scale (<LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>).</P>
</SUBSECTION>
</INCLUDED_STUDIES_DESCR>
<EXCLUDED_STUDIES_DESCR MODIFIED="2014-06-05 13:23:19 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="6">Ongoing studies: </HEADING>
<P>Nil</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="6">Studies awaiting classification</HEADING>
<P>Nil</P>
</SUBSECTION>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="6">New studies found at this update</HEADING>
<P>Not applicable. </P>
</SUBSECTION>
</EXCLUDED_STUDIES_DESCR>
</STUDY_DESCRIPTION>
<STUDY_QUALITY MODIFIED="2014-11-03 15:00:55 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Christopher Gale">
<ALLOCATION MODIFIED="2014-06-05 13:23:29 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>As shown in <LINK REF="FIG-01" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 1</LINK> and <LINK REF="FIG-02" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 2</LINK> all three studies (<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>, <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>, <LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>) were rated as having an unclear risk in that the randomisation processes were not described and there was no discussion about concealment.</P>
</ALLOCATION>
<BLINDING MODIFIED="2014-06-05 13:24:21 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Although all studies were described as "double-blind" , all studies (<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>) had an unclear risk in that there was no discussion about the methods of blinding, or how successful it was.. See <LINK REF="FIG-01" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 1</LINK> and <LINK REF="FIG-02" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 2</LINK>
</P>
</BLINDING>
<EXCLUSIONS MODIFIED="2014-06-05 13:24:37 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>Only one of the studies (<LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>) was judged to be of low risk. This study made explicit explicit use of an intention to treat and LOCF analysis and at least three quarters of participants completed the trial. Two studies (<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>) were described as intention to treat although this method was not described and the number of drop-outs, other than immediately post randomisation, was not identified. See <LINK REF="FIG-01" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 1</LINK> and <LINK REF="FIG-02" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 2</LINK>
</P>
</EXCLUSIONS>
<SELECTIVE_REPORTING MODIFIED="2014-06-05 13:25:20 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>As seen in <LINK REF="FIG-01" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 1</LINK> and <LINK REF="FIG-02" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 2</LINK> all outcomes were reported by all studies(<LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>).</P>
</SELECTIVE_REPORTING>
<OTHER_BIAS_SOURCES MODIFIED="2014-06-05 13:29:43 +1200" MODIFIED_BY="[Empty name]">
<P>All three studies were sponsored by a pharmaceutical company: all studies involved a mixed group of outpatients andpeople who answered advertisements in local publications. One study <LINK REF="STD-Feltner-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Feltner 2003</LINK> alllowed co occuring anxity disorders but not mood disorders, while two papers <LINK REF="STD-Pande-2003" TYPE="STUDY">Pande 2003</LINK>; <LINK REF="STD-Rickels-2005" TYPE="STUDY">Rickels 2005</LINK>, excluded all comorbid conditions. See <LINK REF="FIG-01" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 1</LINK> and <LINK REF="FIG-02" TYPE="FIGURE">Figure 2</LINK>
</P>
</OTHER_BIAS_SOURCES>
</STUDY_QUALITY>
<INTERVENTION_EFFECTS MODIFIED="2014-11-03 15:02:02 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Christopher Gale">
<P/>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="3">Comparison 1. Benzodiazepines versus pregabalin.</HEADING>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="4">Primary outcomes</HEADING>
<SUBSECTION>
<HEADING LEVEL="5">1.1 EFFICACY - Number of participants who responded to treatment (response defined as: 50% decrease in HAM-A)</HEADING>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a higher response rate (defined as 50% decrease in HAM-A) than pregabalin (Risk Ratio (RR) 0.95, 95% confidence interval (CI) 0.77 to 1.16, p=0.60, 3 trials, 678 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.01" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.1</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.2 EFFICACY - Number of participants who responded to treatment (response defined by authors)</B>
</P>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a higher response rate (defined by the authors) than pregabalin (RR 1.00, 95% CI 0.85 to 1.19, p=0.87, 3 trials, 677 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.02" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.2</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.3 ACCEPTABILITY - Total drop-out rate</B>
</P>
<P>There was evidence that pregabalin were associated with a higher number of drop-outs that benzodiazepines (RR 1.79, 95% CI 1.35 to 2.36,p &lt; 0.0001, 3 trials, 774 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.03" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.3</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>Secondary Outcomes</B>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.4 EFFICACY - Number of participants who remitted (remission defined as HAM-A less than seven).</B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trial data reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.5 EFFICACY - Number of participants who remitted (remission defined by the authors).</B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trial data reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>1<B>.6 EFFICACY CONTINUOUS OUTCOME - Mean Difference in HAM-A scores.</B>
</P>
<P>There was a trend towards pregabalin showing greater reduction in HAM-A than benzodiazepines defined by the Mean Difference in the Hamilton Anxiety Scale (Mean Difference, but this was not significant 0.64, 95% CI -0.14 to 1.42, p=0.11, 3 trials, 1043 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.06" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.6</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.7 EFFICACY CONTINUOUS OUTCOME - Mean difference in CGI scores.</B>
</P>
<P>There was was a trend towards an association of benzodiazepines with a difference in CGI compared to pregabalin in CGI scores (Mean Difference 0.17, 95% CI -0.01 to 0.34, p=0.06, 1 trial, 525 participants) See <LINK REF="CMP-001.07" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.7</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.8 EFFICACY CONTINUOUS OUTCOME - Mean Difference in STAI -state scores.</B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.9 EFFICACY CONTINUOUS OUTCOME - Mean difference in Covi anxiety scale scores. </B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.10 EFFICACY CONTINUOUS OUTCOME - Mean difference in STAI-trait scores.</B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.11 QUALITY OF LIFE OUTCOME - Mean difference in Q-LES-Q-SF scores</B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.12 ACCEPTABILITY - Total number of participants reporting at least one side effect</B>
</P>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a statistically significant difference in the total number of participants reporting at least one side effect compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenzel Risk Ratio (RR) 1.12, CI 0.91 to 1.38, p=0.28, 1 trial, 204 participants.</P>
<P>
<B>1.13 ACCEPTABILITY - Number of participants reporting withdrawal</B>
</P>
<P>We could not find any trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.14 Side effect - Sleepiness or drowsiness </B>
</P>
<P>There was evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a statistically significant higher number of participants reporting sleepiness or drowsiness, compared to pregabalin (Mantel Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 1.80, CI 1.21 to 2.68,m, p=0.003, 3 trials, 809 participants. See <LINK REF="CMP-001.14" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.14</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.15 Side effect -- Weight gain or increased appetite</B>
</P>
<P>We could find no trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.16 Side effect -- Hypotension or dizziness or lightheadedness</B>
</P>
<P>There was evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a statistically significant lower number of participants reporting hypotension or light headedness or dizziness compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 1.80, CI 0.34 to 0.66, p &lt; 0.00001, 3 trials, 774 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.16" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.16</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.17 Side effect -- Fatigue or Lethargy</B>
</P>
<P>There was evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a statistically significant higher number of participants reporting fatigue or lethargy, compared to pregabalin (Mantel Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 1.74, CI 1.09 to 2.77, p=0.02, 3 trials, 774 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.17" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.17</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.18 Side effect -- Headache</B>
</P>
<P>There was evidence that benzodiaepines were associated with a statistically significant lower number of participants reporting headache compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 0.47, CI 0.25 to 0.88, p=0.02, 2 trials, 411 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.18" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.18</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.19 Side effect -- Anxiety or agitation</B>
</P>
<P>We could find no trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.20 Side effect -- Insomnia</B>
</P>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with insomnia compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 2.69, CI 0.61 to 11.91, p=0.19, 1 trial, 207 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.20" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.20</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.21 Side effect -- Memory Impairment</B>
</P>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with memory impairment compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 2.22, CI 0.78 to 6.31, p=0.13, 2 trials, 411 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.21" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.21</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.22 Side effect -- Driving Impairment</B>
</P>
<P>We could find no trials reporting this outcome.</P>
<P>
<B>1.23 Side effect -- Mood change including depression</B>
</P>
<P>We could find no trials reporting this outcome</P>
<P>
<B>1.24 Side effects -- falls, ataxia or accidental injury</B>
</P>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with side effects including falls, ataxia or accidental injury compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 0.85, CI 0.29 to 2.48, p=0.76, 3 trials, 774 participants. See <LINK REF="CMP-001.24" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.24</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<B>1.25 Acceptability -- (withdrawal due to side effects)</B>
</P>
<P>There was evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with a statistically significant higher number of withdrawals due to side effects compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio (RR) 1.90, CI 1.20 to 3.01, p=0.006, 3 trials, 708 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.25" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.25</LINK>
</P>
<P>
<I>
<B>1.26 Acceptability (withdrawal due to inefficiency) </B>
</I>
</P>
<P>There was no evidence that benzodiazepines were associated with withdrawals due to inefficiency compared to pregabalin (Mantel-Haenszel Risk Ratio 0.80, CI 0.19 to 3.36, p=0.76, 2 trials, 570 participants). See <LINK REF="CMP-001.26" TYPE="ANALYSIS">Analysis 1.26</LINK>
</P>
</SUBSECTION>
</SUBSECTION>
</SUBSECTION>
</INTERVENTION_EFFECTS>
</RESULTS>
<DISCUSSION MODIFIED="2012-11-22 01:30:43 +1300" MODIFIED_BY="Jessica Sharp">
